Given that the power of model A and B chuvies is 4400 W and the resistance of a battery in model A is R_A = V / I_A and in model B is R_B = V / I_B where V is voltage and I is current.

The equation for power is P = IV so given that the power is 4400 w in both models, we can solve for the current I as follows:

I_A = V / R_A

I_B = V / R_B

P = I_A * R_A = I_B * R_B

4400 = (V / R_A) * R_A = (V / R_B) * R_B

Since both chuvies have the same power, their resistance values must be inversely proportional to each other. Therefore, we can calculate the ratio of the two resistances as follows:

R\_A : R\_B = I\_B : I\_A

I\_B = 0.4 * I\_A (given that it is 40% less) so the ratio of their resistances is:

R\_A : R\_B = I\_B / I\_A = 0.4 / 1
